            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.26a.102-104_0001"/>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>Dear Mr. Neihardt:</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>I am writing this at the office, and the stationary drawer is temporarily blocked by a business conference, so please excuse the paper.</p>
                
                <p>I am enclosing the essay written by John of which I spoke, thinking you might enjoy seeing it. Also enclosed is a verse I wrote.</p>
                
                <p>T<del>j</del><add>h</add>ank you again for the very constructive criticisms you gave. It was a great treat for us to have met you and heard you talk.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Cordially,</salute>
                
                    <signed>Marjorie B. Davis</signed>
                    <signed>Mrs. Deane Davis</signed>
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>112½ South Duluth Ave.</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Sioux Falls, <hi rend="caps">S. D.</hi></addrLine>
                    </address>
                </closer>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">10<del>3</del><add>2</add></fw>
                    
            </div1>
            
            
            <div1 type="enclosure">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.26a.102-104_0002"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">10<del>4</del><add>3</add></fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <hi rend="caps">MORNING SNOW</hi>
                
                    By John Baillie Davis - 1940
                    (seventeen years old)
                </opener>
                <p>One morning, when I awoke, I gazed upon one of the most inspirational scenes I have ever<del>y</del>witnessed. So beautiful and entrancing it was that I dared not stir lest it depart from me.</p>
                
                <p>The snow was falling. Nothing was moving, nothing was living, but the falling, falling snow. Futile man with all his guile and cleverness could nowhere be seen; he dare not be seen, for this was the time of the snow.</p>
                
                <p>The world is wicked, plagued with the spreading fungi of war. Peaceful, security-loving nations are being swallowed by the unquenchable thirst for power. But here the heavens, with all the patience of the ages were obliter<del>ing</del><add>ati</add>ng the crooked paths of man, and spreading for him a new and untrodden day.</p>
                
                <p>How dare they call it a "white and trackless waste;" white and trackless - true - but never a waste. It is our future throwing to us a challenge: "Track me clean and straight, and I shall be all you could desire me to be; but track me yet again crooked and foul and then truly I shall be a waste.</p>
                
                <p>That was the vision that came to me that early morning hour as I lay in my bed contemplating the snow from my window - just falling snow in an oppressive silence that was in itself symbolic of the deed that was being done. Somehow the snow became to me the silent tears of a mother seeking to erase the hopeless follies of her mad sons.</p>
                
                <p>The slate lies clean before us, waiting to be decorated as we choose. Shall it be covered, as our ancestors defiled their slates before us, with the repetitious errors of time, with strife, with prejudic<del>9</del><add>e</add> and blind adherence to f<del>llo</del><add>ool</add>ish causes, or shall we decorate it with a new order of things - a design cleansed of the <del>vi</del><add>ev</add>ils of the past? The choice rests wholly in our hands; the challenge has been thrown. How shall we track the snow today?</p>
                
                <milestone unit="section"/><ab><del>m</del>--------</ab>
                
                <note>(T/Sgt. John Baillie Davis was killed in action May 19, 1944.)</note>
                
